==English==
===Etymology===
[[Russian]] [[дворник]] "concierge; one who takes care of the pavement and yard in front of a house", from [[двор]] "courtyard"
===Noun===
'''dvornik'''
# a [[doorman]], [[porter]], [[janitor]], or [[groundskeeper]] in a [[Russian]] [[household]]
#*'''1901:''' Maxim Gorky, ''The Man Who Was Afraid'' - Go to my dvornik and help him to remove the dung. I will pay you.
#*'''1911:''' Joseph Conrad, ''Under Western Eyes'' - Go to my dvornik and help him to remove the dung.
#*'''1912:''' Mary Antin, ''Promised Land'' - My mother kept a cook and a nursemaid, and a '''dvornik''', or outdoor man, to take care of the horses, the cow, and the woodpile.

===Source===
* ''The Oxford English Dictionary''